129. 30. neque all . . . potuissent. This pluperfect is often used in this way instead of the imperfect, inasmuch as the possibility of the thing is represented as the condition which must be fulfilled before the thing itself can take place. Comp. DeOffic. 11‚3, 12: nequeenim ualetudinis curatio neque ogni cultura . . ,sine hominum opera ullu esse potuisset: · Ibid. c. 4,15: quid enumerem artium multitudinem, sine quibus vita omuino nulla esse potuisset.
